60. The papyrus plant was grown principally in Egypt. It grpws in water two or three feet deep, and the plant reaches a height oi five or six teet. The methodos manu- facturing writing material from it is described by· Pliny.⁸ The stem of the plant was cut into thin strips, and these strips were laid parallel to one another upon a smooth sur- iace3 another set ol strips was laid upon these at right angles, and the two layers were glued together by the gum which exuded from the strips when they were moistened with water. The layers were then hammered together into a single sheet, called a plagula, which was exposed to the sun to dry. The sheets were from 5 to 10 inches long, and probably one sufficed tor an ordinary letter. Ii more space was needed, several sheets were pasted together. The center of the papyrus ·industry was Alexandria.
